==English==

===Etymology===
From {{suffix|absolute|ness}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈabsəluːtnəs/|/absəˈluːtnəs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.sə.ˌlut.nəs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|es}}

# {{context|obsolete}} The fact of being [[finished]] or [[perfected]]; [[completeness]]. {{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# Absolute [[authority]], unlimited power; [[despotism]]. {{defdate|First attested in the 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}
#* '''1603''', {{w|John Florio}}, translating Michel de Montaigne, ''Essays'', II.8:
#*: I know no man that could produce more parts, both naturall and artificiall, fit to preserve his masterie, and to maintaine his '''absolutenesse''', than he doth; yet is hee cleane falne from them like a childe.
# The fact of being without qualifications or conditions; [[certainty]], unconditionality. {{defdate|First attested in the 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}
# Independent [[autonomy]]. {{defdate|First attested in the 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}

